    "type": "article",
    "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Ocean",
    "title": "Indian Ocean",
    "content": "The Indian Ocean is the third largest ocean, covering about 20% of the Earth's water surface, and is bordered by Asia, Africa, and Australia. Its unique geography, including the relatively shallow northern regions and the deep Java Trench, influences its complex circulation patterns, which are heavily affected by monsoons. The ocean basin is geologically active, featuring the Carlsberg Ridge and the Ninety East Ridge. Economically, it is vital for shipping routes connecting Europe, the Middle East, Africa, and Asia, carrying significant volumes of oil and trade goods. Biologically, it hosts diverse marine life, though it faces challenges from pollution and overfishing, particularly in its coastal zones.",
    "snippet": "The Indian Ocean is the third largest of the world's five oceans, covering approximately 70.56 million square kilometers (27.24 million square miles). It is bounded by Asia to the north, Africa to the west, and Australia to the east, and is connected to the Southern Ocean in the south. The ocean is strategically important due to its role in global trade and its diverse marine ecosystems.",
    "created_at": "2026-01-20T18:53:47.602197Z",
